# Next.js Server Component Rules

## Never call `buttonVariants()` from a server component

`button.tsx` is `"use client"`. Importing `buttonVariants` from it will throw:
> _"Attempted to call buttonVariants() from the server"_

**Fix:** Import directly from the variants file which has no client directive.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — button.tsx is "use client"
import { buttonVariants } from "@/components/ui/button"

// ✅ GOOD — button-variants.ts has no "use client"
import { buttonVariants } from "@/components/ui/button-variants"
```

The rule: **server components that need `buttonVariants` must import from `@/components/ui/button-variants`**. Client components (`"use client"`) may import from either.

## Never call client functions as plain functions in server components

If a module is marked `"use client"`, its exported functions cannot be invoked on the server — they can only be rendered as JSX or passed as props.

Check the first line of any UI component file before importing it into a server component. If it starts with `"use client"`, you can:
- Render it as JSX (`<Button>`) ✓
- Import pure helpers from a separate non-client file ✓
- Move the consuming code into a `"use client"` component ✓

You cannot call its exports as functions (`buttonVariants()`, `cn(something)` from a client module, etc.).

## Never import values from `@mcp-gcse/db` in client components

`@mcp-gcse/db` exports the Prisma client which uses Node.js-only modules (`node:module` etc). Importing any **value** from it in a `"use client"` component will bundle Prisma into the browser and throw a build error.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — pulls Prisma into the client bundle
import { SUBJECTS, SUBJECT_VALUES } from "@mcp-gcse/db"
import type { Subject } from "@mcp-gcse/db" // ✅ type-only is fine (erased at compile time)

// ✅ GOOD — use the client-safe copy
import { SUBJECTS, SUBJECT_VALUES, type Subject } from "@/lib/subjects"
```

Rules:
- `"use server"` files (server actions): may import values from `@mcp-gcse/db` freely
- `"use client"` files: **only `import type`** from `@mcp-gcse/db`. For values like `SUBJECTS`, import from `@/lib/subjects` instead
- Server components (no directive): same as server actions — value imports are fine

## Hydration errors from `next-themes` / dark mode

`next-themes`' `ThemeProvider` injects `style="color-scheme: light|dark"` onto the `<html>` element **on the server** via its default `enableColorScheme={true}`. The client-side render won't carry that attribute until JS runs, causing a React hydration mismatch.

**Always** add `suppressHydrationWarning` to the root `<html>` element when `ThemeProvider` is in use. This is the [canonical next-themes recommendation](https://github.com/pacocoursey/next-themes#with-app).

Do **not** use `typeof window !== 'undefined'` or `window` checks anywhere in the root layout — that produces the same class of hydration error.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — suppressHydrationWarning silences the expected color-scheme mismatch
<html lang="en" className={`${plusJakartaSans.variable} ${haveIdea.variable}`} suppressHydrationWarning>

// ❌ BAD — missing suppressHydrationWarning when ThemeProvider is present
<html lang="en" className={`${plusJakartaSans.variable} ${haveIdea.variable}`}>

// ❌ BAD — window check in root layout causes its own hydration error
<html lang="en" className={typeof window !== 'undefined' ? 'loaded' : ''}>
```
